data.text: To dive, jump, or throw oneself.
data.attributionText: from The American Heritage® Dictionary of the English Language, 5th Edition.
from The American Heritage® Dictionary of the English Language, 5th Edition.
examples: The car went off the road and plunged into the gully.

data.text: To devote oneself to or undertake an activity earnestly or wholeheartedly.
data.attributionText: from The American Heritage® Dictionary of the English Language, 5th Edition.
examples: I plunged into my studies. She plunged ahead with her plan.

data.text: To enter or move headlong through something.
data.attributionText: from The American Heritage® Dictionary of the English Language, 5th Edition.
examples: The hunting dogs plunged into the forest.

data.attributionText: from The American Heritage® Dictionary of the English Language, 5th Edition.
examples: a cliff that plunges to the sea.

data.text: To move forward and downward violently.
data.attributionText: from The American Heritage® Dictionary of the English Language, 5th Edition.
examples: The ship plunged through rough seas.

data.text: To become suddenly lower; decrease dramatically.
data.attributionText: from The American Heritage® Dictionary of the English Language, 5th Edition.
examples: Stock prices plunged during the banking crisis.

data.text: To thrust or throw forcefully into a substance or place.
data.attributionText: from The American Heritage® Dictionary of the English Language, 5th Edition.
examples: plunged the eggs into the hot water; plunged the fork into the potato.

data.text: To cast suddenly, violently, or deeply into a given state or situation.
data.attributionText: from The American Heritage® Dictionary of the English Language, 5th Edition.
